definition.value: A dipeptide composed of L-glutamic acid and glycine joined by a peptide linkage.
Any naphthyridine derivative that is a derivative of 1,8-naphthyridine.
Any organonitrogen heterocyclic compound that is a derivative of a naphthyridine.
Any naphthyridine derivative that is a derivative of 1,5-naphthyridine.
A sulfur-containing amino acid that is L-aspartic acid substituted at position 3 by a methylthio group.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of methyl (R)-lactate and methyl (S)-lactate.
An L-tryptophan derivative that is L-tryptophan-6,7-dione in which a cysteine unit is attached at position 4 via its side-chain thiol group.
A carbamoylkanamycin that is kanamycin A bearing a single carbamoyl substituent located at position 6'' (on the 3-aminoglucose ring).
Any kanamycin carrying one or more carbamoyl substituents
A carbamoylkanamycin that is tobramycin bearing a single carbamoyl substituent located at position 6'' (on the 3-aminoglucose ring).
An L-alpha-amino acid which is biosynthesised from erythrose 4-phosphate and phosphoenolpyruvate (i.e. phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan). A closed class.

A carbonyl compound produced as a water-soluble byproduct when fatty acids are broken down for energy in the liver. There are three endogenous ketone bodies: acetone, acetoacetic acid, and (R)-3-hydroxybutyric acid; others may be produced as a result of the metabolism of synthetic triglycerides.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of the two carboxy goups of bromosuccinic acid.

A macrolide antibiotic that is erythromycin A in which the ketone group has been converted to the corresponding imine and then reduced to give the corresponding amino compound (the 9S diastereoisomer).
A dicarboxylic acid that is succinic acid substituted at position 2 by a bromine atom.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is nonane with two  carboxylic acid groups at positions C-1 and C-9.
A dodecatetraenedioic acid with double bonds at positions 2, 4, 8, and 10 (all E isomer).
A  alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is a C12 acid having four double bonds at unspecified positions in the chain.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is undecane substituted by carboxylic acid groups at positions C-1 and C-11.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,14-dicarboxy derivative of tetradecane.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,18-dicarboxy derivative of octadecane.
A carbohydrate derivative in which one or more of the oxygens or hydroxy groups of the parent carbohydrate is replaced by sulfur or -SR, where R can be hydrogen or any group.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-threonine residues.
A L-histidine derivative that is L-histidine substituted at poisition 2 (on the imidazole ring) by a 3-carboxylato-3-(trimethylammonio)propyl group.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-histidine residues.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-O-acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 32:1 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are tetradecanoyl and (11Z)-octadec-11-enoyl respectively.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 14:1 in which the remaining acyl group is (9Z)-tetradecenoyl.
A dipeptide formed from glycyl and L-glutamic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from glycyl and L-aspartic acid residues.
A 1-O-(alk-1-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alk-1-enyl group contains 16 carbons and no additional double bonds.
A  lysophosphatidylcholine P-16:0 in which the alk-1-enyl group is hexadec-1-en-1-yl.
A  1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 1-acyl group is (9Z)-hexadecenoyl (palmitoleoyl).

A lysophosphatidylcholine in which the remaining acyl group contains 17 carbons and 1 double bond. If R1 is acyl and R2 is a hydrogen then the molecule is a 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine. If R1 is a hydrogen and R2 is acyl then the molecule is a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.
A  1-O-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the  1-acyl group is (10Z)-heptadecenoyl.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:0 in which the acyl substituent is located at position 1 and is specified as stearoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 40:5 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are octadecanoyl and (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-docosapentaenoyl respectively.
A phosphatidylcholine 40:6 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are (11Z)-octadecenoyl and (7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosapentaenoyl respectively.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:6 in which the remaining acyl group is (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosa-4,7,10,13,16,19-hexaenoyl.
A dipeptide formed from glycine and L-glutamine residues.
A member of the class of pteridines that is pteridine in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 4 are replaced by amino groups, whilst those at positions 6 and 7 are replaced by isopropyl groups.

A D-aldohexose that is D-glucose in which the hydrogen of the hydroxy group at position 3 has been substituted by a methyl group. It is a non-metabolisable glucose analogue that is not phosphorylated by hexokinase and is used as a marker to assess glucose transport by evaluating its uptake within various cells and organ systems.
A thiazolidinemonocarboxylic acid  that is L-thioproline with a sulfomethyl group at position 2.
A hydroxybutyric acid that is butyric acid  substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2, 2 and 4.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid and phosphate monoester that is adipic acid with a phosphate group at position 4 and hydroxy groups at positions 2, 3, and 5.
A phosphatidylcholine 32:1 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are hexadecanoyl and (9Z)-hexadec-9-enoyl respectively.
An icosanoid that is leukotriene E4 in which the non-conjugated double bond has been reduced to a single bond and four methylene groups have been lost from the resulting carboxyalkyl chain.

An icosanoid that is leukotriene E4 in which the isolated double bond has migrated into conjugation with the triene moiety and in which four methylene groups have been lost from the resulting carboxyalkyl chain.
An icosanoid that is leukotriene E4 in which two methylene groups are removed from the carboxyalkyl chain attached to the non-conjugated double bond.
